<DOC><DOCNO> AP880318-0055 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-18-88 0657EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     03-18 0560</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0576</SECOND><HEAD>Midwest, South Dusted With Light Snow</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   A storm dusted the Midwest and parts of the South today withsnow after snapping power lines and closing schools in Arkansas.   ``There were people who planned to lay out in bikinis, andthey're packing up their snow suits,'' said Donna Dickey, aUniversity of Arkansas student whose spring break began today.   The storm knocked out power to about 3,000 homes and businessesThursday, Arkansas Power andamp; Light Co. spokesman Charles Kelly said.   Harrison, Ark., reported 22 inches of snow on the ground, whilemost northern parts of the state had 4 to 8 inches.   Forecasters posted winter storm warnings for nothern Arkansasand western Kentucky. Snow advisories also were posted for southernIllinois, western Tennessee, southern Indiana, Ohio, northern WestVirginia and southwest Pennsylvania.   Early today, snow fell across lower Michigan, southwest Ohio,Indiana, Illinois, southern and eastern Missouri and northwestKentucky. Rain and snow fell across southeast Missouri andsouthwest Kentucky. Rain fell in western Tennessee, Arkansas,Mississippi, Louisiana and eastern Texas.   Snowfall during the six hours ending at 1 a.m. EST included aninch at Columbia, St. Louis and Springfield, Mo. During the sameperiod, Galveston, Texas, had nearly 2 inches, Lake Charles, La.,had slightly more than an inch and Palacios, Texas, had aboutthree-quarters of an inch.   The temperature in Midland, Texas, dropped to 23 degrees, tyingthe record low for the date set in 1934.   In Florida, a cold snap that sent temperatures to record lowsshowed signs of easing today. The cold did little damage to crops,officials said.   Today's forecast called for snow from southeast Missouri andeastern Arkansas across much of Tennessee and the Ohio Valley intothe central Appalachians and New York state; snow scattered overMichigan; rain and thunderstorms from the central Gulf Coast statesacross east Tennessee, Georgia and northern and central Florida;rain spreading east across the Carolinas; and scattered rain alongthe middle Atlantic Coast.   Highs were expected to be in the 40s or 50s in much of thenation; the 30s from North Dakota across the upper MississippiValley, the Ohio Valley and the Great Lakes into northern NewEngland; the 60s and 70s over the West Coast and western portionsof the Plateau, Florida and southern Georgia; the 60s along thecentral Gulf Coast and along the coast of the Carolinas; and the80s over much of the desert Southwest.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 1degree below zero at Laramie, Wyo., to 70 at Key West, Fla.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 46 cloudy; Boston 35 fair; Buffalo 27 cloudy;Charleston, S.C. 38 foggy; Cincinnati 32 snow; Cleveland 33 cloudy;Detroit 34 cloudy; Miami 66 fair; New York 35 fair; Philadelphia 33partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 29 cloudy; Portland, Maine 26 fair;Washington 34 cloudy.   _Central: Bismarck 25 fair; Chicago 31 snow; Dallas-Fort Worth37 windy; Denver 17 fair; Des Moines 23 fair; Indianapolis 32 snow;Kansas City 24 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 27 fair; Nashville 40cloudy; New Orleans 55 rain; St. Louis 32 snow.   _West: Albuquerque 26 fair; Anchorage 31 cloudy; Las Vegas 46fair; Los Angeles 57 fair; Phoenix 58 fair; Salt Lake City 29 fair;San Diego 55 fair; San Francisco 48 fair; Seattle 46 fair.   _Canada: Montreal 27 fair; Toronto 27 foggy.</TEXT></DOC>